documents.t: Why you need a code editor (or IDE)
02 - Join Digital Law Lab organisation on GitHub
This Chapter contains information about conventions you should follow to ensure consistency and clarity across the team.

This guidebook contains important information you need to ensure that your PC is set up correctly and that you can complete you work seamlessly, in accordance with the required procedures. It doesn't contain documentation about Docassemble itself. For quick navigation, you can either use the search box at the top or use the sidebar to the right. tip For Docassemble's documentation visit docassemble.org

If you are new head to Setting Up. If you want to join our team see How to join us. Otherwise, the workflow would be as follows: create a new branch clone the branch to your local PC create a corresponding 'Project' in your Docassemble playground for testing open the cloned folder in your code editor and start coding use docassemble_playground_manager to push code from your PC to your Docassemble Project test and run Commit and push changes to GitHub make a pull request to main for code reviews and for promotion to production Remember if further work is required later, repeat from step 1 and make sure to pull the most recent stable version to avoid merge conflicts. tip The Digital-Law-Lab repository has the utility scripts we use for pushing code from VS Code to Docassemble. Peruse the following chapters for more detailed explanation on each step.
This Chapter explains how you can contribute to this guide.
This Chapter briefly introduces important concepts about the tools we commonly use.
clone (and only a specific branch with the -b flag) new branch switch branch add Commit push (origin and branch name) pull request or use vscode extensions and built in features

We don't use Docassemble's Playground to edit code. This is because the Playground is too small and also doesn't work so well with Github. Instead, we use a code editor like Visual Studio Code and some custom python scripts to do our editing work and push our code to Docassemble for testing.

The first step is to find yourself a decent code editor - if you don't already have one. We recommend Visual Studio Code, for its enormous library of extensions and great Developer Experience. You could of course use other options, like Sublime Text, Atom [deprecated], or even Vim üò≤ (or, use Vim bindings for VSCode - if you want to ü§Ø).
IntelliSense is by far the most appealing advantage of using a powerful IDE like VSCode. It provides things like auto-completion and error spotting (aka linting), among other handy features.

We recommend that you store all files related to DLL in a single directory. It is up to you what to name the folder and where to store it. You could put it on you Desktop or in %USERPROFILE% (normally c:\Users\[your username]). It just needs to be in a place you can easily access and won't quickly forget. Of course, you should resist any temptation to put it in your Downloads folder (especially if your regularly purge your Downloads).
We use a Docassemble server to run and test our code before pushing to GitHub. This way we can ensure that everything runs as expected and no unintentional bugs were caused.

GitHub is a remote repository we use to store our project files and utility scripts. Git is a local version control system which allows you to communicate with a remote repository stored on GitHub ‚Äî by downloading (pulling), or uploading (pushing) changes. A list of important terms is provided below.
If you don't already have an account (or if you want a new one), create one here.
You need to associate git with your GitHub account.

caution You should already have a developer account on our server - if not see Obtaining a developer account. There are several paradigms for testing your code and ensuring that the logic operates as expected. The primary way we test our beloved code is by sending the application to our Docassemble server and running it.

Make sure that you have your API key - if you missed the step refer to this section. TODO tip Remember to always edit the code in VSCode and not the playground. After you have fixed any error and saved your changes, push again to the server and test. Repeat this until you have resolved all issues and are ready to push to GitHub for review. info Don't forget to commit your changes occasionally (even if you don't plan to push to GitHub yet). This way you can revert to an older copy when you break stuff (I am confident we all will)!
